numen...genium: emperor worship began with Julius Caesar, to whom statues and altars were erected and a temple under the title of Jupiter Julius (Dio 44. 63 Suet. I. Caes. 88). From the Eastern provinces the worship of the numen Auyusti spread to the West. In Rome Augustus refused to receive such honours (Suet. Oct. 52), but subsequent emperors encouraged the cult. From the begining the emperors actively encouraged the worship of the Imperial Genius (see D'Alton, Horace ancl lzis Aye, pp. 57 ff. ; Warde Fowler, Roman Ideas of Deity, pp. 90 ff. 3 Ε.
